      "text": "I still think that having many people editing one FedWiki will be too many cooks in the kitchen, so I thought of something in between. You can have a permission system, when one person owns the wiki and can edit it, but few other people can also login, and fork content onto the wiki. So they don't edit anything, they just add pages that they think are good to the wiki."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "68460dd0ce7db37e",
      "text": "This might create a strange social dynamic through introducing a role of crawlers and forkers. They wouldnt have a voice on a wiki, in a sense that they can edit stuff, but they can have a this \"central\" wiki open in a browser tab and just drop stuff there that they think are relevant, and press \"fork\". "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "42782db96c91a51b",
      "text": "It might create some weird bugs, such as what happens if they fork a page with the same name? They will overwrite it. So it is even more power than editing. May be they shouldn't be able to overwrite pages, I mean they wont be able to fork pages with the same name. The attempt to do so will just bring up a url with an existing page, so they can see it is already forked, but I'm not sure. May be they are allowed to overwrite a page, ut without overwriting the history of the one which existed there before."
